problem:
A uniform thin string of length \(l\) with a mass per unit length of \(\eta\) is performing small transverse oscillations in the plane \((x, y)\). Its endpoints \((0,0)\) and \((l, 0)\) are fixed with a tension of \(\tau\), and during oscillations, it experiences frictional forces related to velocity. If an infinitesimally small segment of length \(\delta l\) has a transverse velocity \(v\), the frictional force is \(-\gamma v \delta l\). The small oscillations \(y(x, t)\) satisfy the following partial differential equation and boundary conditions:

\[
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\partial^{2} y}{\partial t^{2}}+a \frac{\partial y}{\partial t}=b \frac{\partial^{2} y}{\partial x^{2}} \\
y(0, t)=0, \quad y(l, t)=0
\end{gathered}
\]

(1) Write the constants \(a\) and \(b\);

solution:
Using Newton's law of motion for the segment of the string between \(x\) and \(x+\mathrm{d} x\),

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \eta \mathrm{d} x \frac{\partial^{2} y}{\partial t^{2}}=\left.\tau \frac{\partial y}{\partial x}\right|_{x+\mathrm{d} x}-\left.\tau \frac{\partial y}{\partial x}\right|_{x}-\gamma \frac{\partial y}{\partial t} \mathrm{d} x \\
= & \tau \frac{\partial^{2} y}{\partial x^{2}} \mathrm{d} x-\gamma \frac{\partial y}{\partial t} \mathrm{d} x \\
& \frac{\partial^{2} y}{\partial t^{2}}+\frac{\gamma}{\eta} \frac{\partial y}{\partial t}=\frac{\tau}{\eta} \frac{\partial^{2} y}{\partial x^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Therefore,

\[
a=\frac{\gamma}{\eta}, \quad b=\frac{\tau}{\eta}
\]

