That is

\begin{gather*}
\frac{\mathrm{d} x}{\mathrm{~d} t}=x+t \\
\frac{\mathrm{~d} y}{\mathrm{~d} t}=-(y-t) \tag{1}
\end{gather*}

Both are non-homogeneous first-order linear differential equations with constant coefficients. We use the method of variation of parameters, first finding the solution to the corresponding homogeneous equations.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\mathrm{d} x}{\mathrm{~d} t}=x \\
& x=c \mathrm{e}^{t}
\end{aligned}
$$

Changing the constant $c$ into a function of $t$

\begin{gather*}
x=c(t) \mathrm{e}^{t} \tag{2} \\
\dot{x}=\dot{c} \mathrm{e}^{t}+c \mathrm{e}^{t} \tag{3}
\end{gather*}

Substituting equations (2) and (3) into equation (1), we find the differential equation that $c(t)$ satisfies

$$
\begin{aligned}
\dot{c} \mathrm{e}^{t} & =t \\
